, and eateries. 5. Kalka in Shimla Shimla Railway is also a UNESCO World Heritage Site in India's hill railway station. Along with other railway lines in India, the British constructed this rail line to Shimla in 1898. It travels via several popular tourist destinations, including Solan, Summer Hill, and many more, from Kalka (a town in Haryana) to Shimla. If you're travelling to Shimla, you should take this train. This train will provide you with an unforgettable tourism experience with several tunnels, bridges, and spectacular vistas. 6. Green Valley in Shimla On the route from Shimla to Kufri, the Green Valley mountainous region is a stunning view. This Valley is encircled on all sides by barren hills covered with deep deodar and deodar forests. Yaks are frequently spotted wandering and grazing in the Valley. Despite the area's lack of tourism development, travellers are nonetheless drawn to it by the abundant deodar and deodar trees that border the gorgeous hillsides. Rare creatures can also be observed here sometimes. Green Valley has also appeared in several Bollywood films for its beauty and elegance. 7. Tara Devi Temple in Shimla Even though you consider yourself religious or not, you should visit the Tara Devi Temple when you're in Shimla. This temple, located at the top of Tara Parvat hill, is roughly 250 years old. The principal spirit here is also Goddess Tara, a Tibetan Buddhist deity who is one of Goddess Durga's nine sisters. According to local belief, the wooden idol placed in the shrine was imported from West Bengal. At the same time, the temple has a peaceful vibe about it. Tourists are drawn to this location by its architectural beauty. 8. Solan Mushroom City in Shimla Solan, known as the Mushrooms City and the Red Gold City of India, is well-known for producing tomatoes and mushrooms. Tourists that visit this place love it very much because of Solan. Since the British government masterminded the original economic growth of this location, they deserve credit for Sonal's development. The best feature of this location is that it offers pleasant temperatures all year long. This location's stunning natural surroundings will never fail to astound you. 9. Indian Institute of Advanced Studies in Shimla The Indian Institute of Advanced Studies is a magnificent Victorian-style building on a Hill in Shimla. It is currently being used as a college that provides post-doctoral courses. The British government once held important political meetings at the building. The structure, a must-see in Shimla and Manali, was originally constructed as Lord Dufferin's home. He was the Viceroy of India from 1884 to 1888. Its previous name was Viceregal Lodge. Before Shimla would utilise electricity in any way, the structure had an electrical connection as early as 1888. Before becoming the Indian Institute of Advanced Studies, this location served as Rashtrapati Niwas, the president of India's summer residence following the country's independence. 10. Manali Hill Station in Shimla Manali, a well-known hill town in the Indian state of Himachal Pradesh, is well-known for being the home of the Hindu god "Manu." The mountain city of Manali, one of India's most popular hill resorts, is located at the height of 2,050 metres above sea level in the northern Kullu district's Beas river valley. Manali was once inhabited by nomadic hunters and herders who travelled there from the Kangra Valley. 11. Kullu in Shimla With Manali, an open valley with amazing views and imposing hills clothed with luscious green trees, Kullu is a well-known tourist attraction in India. Due to its great views, Kullu, at an elevation of 1230 metres, is one of Himachal Pradesh's most visited tourist destinations. Let's say that most visitors to this area like exploring both Kullu and Manali simultaneously. This little village, which is surrounded by beautiful scenery, will captivate any tourists that come to visit. Additionally, you may go to various significant temples 