e of their religious or cultural importance. However, certain temples are ideal in both circumstances. The Kali Bari Shrine in Shimla, which is devoted to Goddess Kali and features an alluring statue of the Goddess, is one such temple. The temple, constructed in 1845, is also referred to as Shyamala. Shimla is derived from the Goddess Shyamala, and it is the capital of Himachal Pradesh. Between 7 am and 6 pm, the temple is open. 17. Arki Fort in Shimla The architecture of the Arki Fort, constructed in 1660 AD, combines Rajput and Mughal styles. This location might prove to be significant for you if you adore history. The Kangra sculptures that cover the fort are what makes it famous. Even though the sculptures in this fort are said to be almost 200 years old, they nevertheless appear stunning. Include this fort on your list if you are a history enthusiast. 18. Johnnie's Wax Museum in Shimla The biggest draw for tourists is the Johnny Wax Museum, sometimes referred to as the first wax museum in Himachal Pradesh. The Statues of several well-known movie stars are on display at this museum. The museum's wax figures of Harry Potter, Steve Jobs, Mahatma Gandhi, and Tony Stark are among the most popular ones. The best thing is capturing the moment on camera while posing next to your favourite star. The entrance charge to this exhibition is about Rs 250 for seniors and Rs 5 for kids, and it is open from 10 am until 10 pm. 19. Naldehra in Shimla Naldehra, a stunning hill station close to Shimla, is 2044 metres above sea level. A golf course had already been built here by Lord Curzon. The ambience in this location is quite alluring because of the numerous deodar trees and the lovely vegetation. This is a fantastic location to view the Foothills Of the Himalayas. You can hear the voice of the breeze coming here due to the quiet environment. You may ride a horse to get across this area. If you visit, you may find it alluring to view the dawn and sunset in Naldehra. Said, this i