e year, except for the monsoon season from July to September. Famous Food of Shimla Shimla is one of India's most stunning hill towns and is a must-visit location when planning a trip to Himachal Pradesh. In addition to all these things, Himachal Pradesh's capital city is renowned for its delectable Himachali food, a delicious fusion of Tibetan and Punjabi food. In Himachal, most of the diet comprises wheat bread, lentils, pulses, rice, and red meat. The food is primarily nutritious as well as rich and flavorful. Shimla offers a wide variety of delectable cuisine, from street sellers to fine restaurants and traditional cafés. Here is a list of some mouthwatering foods to experience while travelling to Shimla. Madra Sidu Chicken Anardana Dhaam Chha Gosht Thupka Babru Way To Reach Shimla The capital of Himachal Pradesh, Shimla, is one of the most stunning tourist spots in the nation and is home to many magnificent landmarks. Shimla is so unique that visitors rush to all the hill towns all year, making it impossible to escape the crowds. The first thing that comes to mind while planning a trip to Shimla is how effortlessly Shimla can be accessed by air, rail, and road. 1. By Air The closest airport to Shimla is Jubbarhatti, roughly 23 kilometres from the city. If you're travelling there, remember, there are frequent flights from Chandigarh and Delhi to Jubbarhatti. You may get a cab to take you to Shimla after arriving at this airport. 2. By Rail A narrow-gauge rail line connects Shimla's little railway station, which is only one kilometre from the city centre, Kalka. The well-known toy train from Shimla travels 96 kilometres between Kalka and Shimla, covering the route in around 7 hours. Shimla's closest train station is Kalka, with regular trains running from Delhi and other major states. 3. By Road Shimla is well linked by road to towns like Chandigarh, which is 117 km away, Manali, which is 260 km away, and Delhi, which is 343 km away. In addition to Himachal Road 