ke in a variety of sights at The Ridge. Stores here offer unique artefacts, and the snow-covered mountain peaks give breathtaking views. The Ridge's most unique feature is that, during the British era, it was the most exclusive spot to stay during the warmer months. Many people travel to Shimla because it is a stunning location. The Ridge serves as a market and a city's community space. Shimla always used to be crowded with locals and tourists. This avenue also has a lot of popular cafés, clubs, boutiques, stores, and eateries. 5. Kalka in Shimla Shimla Railway is also a UNESCO World Heritage Site in India's hill railway station. Along with other railway lines in India, the British constructed this rail line to Shimla in 1898. It travels via several popular tourist destinations, including Solan, Summer Hill, and many more, from Kalka (a town in Haryana) to Shimla. If you're travelling to Shimla, you should take this train. This train will provide you with an unforgettable tourism experience with several tunnels, bridges, and spectacular vistas. 6. Green Valley in Shimla On the route from Shimla to Kufri, the Green Valley mountainous region is a stunning view. This Valley is encircled on all sides by barren hills covered with deep deodar and deodar forests. Yaks are frequently spotted wandering and grazing in the Valley. Despite the area's lack of tourism development, travellers are nonetheless drawn to it by the abundant deodar and deodar trees that border the gorgeous hillsides. Rare creatures can also be observed here sometimes. Green Valley has also appeared in several Bollywood films for its beauty and elegance. 7. Tara Devi Temple in Shimla Even though you consider yourself religious or not, you should visit the Tara Devi Temple when you're in Shimla. This temple, located at the top of Tara Parvat hill, is roughly 250 years old. The principal spirit here is also Goddess Tara, a Tibetan Buddhist deity who is one of Goddess Durga's nine sisters. According to loca